<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-254-486  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 254 486.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 19 1990 v24 n12 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Complex crimes stall enforcers. (part 2) (computer-related theft)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software theft, in spite of the value of intellectual property,holds a low priority with law enforcement officials because of thecomplicated nature of the crime.andP;  A competitor of Phase LinearSystems stole a tape from a Phase customer containing a copy ofthe company's top mainframe program.andP;  Phase officials reported thetheft to the police.andP;  The thieves admitted the crime but officialshave yet to prosecute because they are busy with a wide range ofmore serious crimes.andP;  Investigation of computer-related crimestakes a great deal of time.andP;  Police say they are more willing toinvestigate these crimes than they have been.andP;  Crimes involvingtelecommunications that cross state and federal jurisdictions areparticularly difficult to solve because collaboration is difficultand carriers are hesitant to cooperate with authorities for fearof being sued for privacy violations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer crimesLaw enforcementInvestigationsComputer virusesComputer hackers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>